
[1]coral

   CORAL, n. [L. Gr.]

   1. In zoology, a genus belonging to the order of vermes zoophyta. The
   trunk is radicated, jointed and calcarious. The species are
   distinguished by the form of their branches, and are found in the ocean
   adhering to stones, bones, shells, &c. Coral was formerly supposed to
   be a vegetable substance, but is now known to be composed of a
   congeries of animals. Coral is red, white and black. It is properly the
   shells of marine animals of the polype kind, consisting of calcarious
   earth combined with gelatine and other animal matter. In the South Sea,
   the isles are mostly coral rocks covered with earth. Corals seem to
   consist of carbonate of lime and animal matter, in equal proportions.

   2. A piece of coral worn by children about their necks.

                 CORAL, a. Made of coral; resembling coral.
